<P>
MARINES ORDERED TO REMOVE TOXIC WASTE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A state water quality agency has ordered officials at the U.S. Marine Corps 
Logistics Base near Barstow to clean up a military landfill where barrels of 
hazardous sandblasting waste are buried. Base spokesmen acknowledge that 
55-gallon drums of the waste routinely were dumped at the landfill, perhaps as 
early as 1961. 
</P>
<P>
But the Marines say they did not know the material contained dangerous levels 
of lead and other heavy metals, thus requiring its disposal at a hazardous 
waste landfill. The order issued by the California Regional Water Quality 
Control Board calls the waste a threat to the area's aquifer, the sole drinking 
water source for several desert communities. It requires base officials to 
complete the clean-up by March, 1991, or face legal action. 
</P>
