<HEADLINE>
<P>
SACRAMENTO FILE: GOVERNOR 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
Compiled by Jerry Gillam, Times staff writer 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Appointed Keith E. McKean of La Mirada to the Orange County Transportation 
Commission. A Republican, McKean, 64, replaces Donald L. Watson of Sacramento, 
who resigned. He currently is a Caltrans district director. Commission members 
are paid necessary expenses. The job does not require Senate confirmation. 
</P>
<P>
Appointed Jacob Margosian of Sacramento to the Workers' Compensation Appeals 
Board. A Republican, Margosian, 63, replaces Marilyn Murata of San Francisco, 
whose term expired. He currently is an assistant director in the Department of 
Rehabilitation. The job pays $88,056 annually and requires Senate confirmation. 
</P>
<P>
Will accept 1 million "drug-free" pledges from elementary school children 
across California in the Ronald Reagan Cabinet Room today. 
</P>
<P>
Assembly 
</P>
<P>
Floor Action: 
</P>
<P>
Rules Committee: Voted 74-0 for Assemblyman Jerry Eaves (D-Rialto) to fill a 
Rules Committee vacancy caused by the election to the Senate of former 
Assemblywoman Lucy Killea (D-San Diego). Killea replaces Sen. Larry Stirling 
(R-San Diego), who was appointed to a Municipal Court judgeship by Gov. George 
Deukmejian. 
</P>
<P>
Campaign Contributions: Denied on a 2-60 vote concurrence in Senate amendments 
to a bill (AB 453) by Assemblyman Steve Peace (D-Chula Vista) to allow 
legislators to use campaign contributions for legal defense court case fees. 
The action sends the measure to a two-house conference committee to try to work 
out a compromise. 
</P>
<P>
Bill Introductions: 
</P>
<P>
Rapid Transit: AB 2541 by Assemblyman Richard Polanco (D-Los Angeles) would 
create a new Southern California Regional Rapid Transit District and clarify 
the scope of activities of the RTD and the Los Angeles County Transportation 
Commission. 
</P>
<P>
Air Pollution: AB 2549 by Assemblywoman Lucille Roybal-Allard (D-Los Angeles) 
would require local air pollution control officers and the Department of Health 
Services to deny permits to applicants with a history of repeated air pollution 
control law violations. 
</P>
<P>
Crane Operators: AB 2537 by Assemblyman John Burton (D-San Francisco) would set 
up a new state crane operators' licensing board in the wake of a recent San 
Francisco crane collapse that killed five people. 
</P>
<P>
Vehicle Fees: AB 2545 by Assemblyman Richard Katz (D-Sylmar) would extend an 
added $1 vehicle registration fee to Jan. 1, 1993, to help finance California 
Highway Patrol operations. The fee is currently scheduled to expire on June 1, 
1991. 
</P>
<P>
Senate 
</P>
<P>
Bill Introductions: 
</P>
<P>
Illegal Aliens: SB 1745 by Sen. John Seymour (R-Anaheim) would order the 
deportation of illegal aliens convicted of felony crimes in California after 
they have completed their prison sentences. 
</P>
<P>
Family Planning: SB 1726 by Sen. Diane Watson (D-Los Angeles) would require 
that all persons eligible for family planning services have the right to 
receive those services, regardless of the source of funding. 
</P>
<P>
Higher Education: SCR 74 by Sen. Gary K. Hart (D-Santa Barbara) would establish 
a joint committee on the expansion of the California higher educational system 
to hold public hearings and develop legislative recommendations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
