<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY FOCUS: SAN CLEMENTE; 
</P>
<P>
FIREFIGHTERS OK PACT RAISING SALARIES 5% 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Ending six months of negotiations, city firefighters have agreed to a new 
four-year contract that includes a 5% annual pay increase, city officials 
announced Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
The new labor agreement is retroactive to July 1 and covers 23 non-management 
fire personnel, Assistant City Manager Gregory L. Hulsizer said. 
</P>
<P>
Besides the pay increase, the contract allows firefighters to retire at age 50 
instead of 55, beginning in 1993. The contract expires June 30, 1993. 
</P>
<P>
General city employees agreed to a new two-year contract in November, Hulsizer 
said. That pact, which affects 160 non-management employees, provides a 5% 
salary increase for fiscal year 1989-90 and a 4 1/2% increase for fiscal year 
1990-91. 
</P>
<P>
Negotiations are continuing with the city's 43-member police force. The city's 
contract with the San Clemente Peace Officers Assn. expired Sunday. The police 
union has complained that, according to a recent union survey, its members are 
the lowest-paid police officers in Orange County. 
</P>
</TEXT>
