<HEADLINE>
<P>
FOR A CATCHY NAME, CONSULT THE PUN &amp; BRADSTREET OF CUTE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
CHICAGO 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Let's Pet is an invitation to . . . buy an animal, A Flush Beats A Full House 
does plumbing and Honest Engines repairs motors. 
</P>
<P>
Punmanship is giving American entrepreneurship a new name, says a University of 
Illinois author whose new book lists dozens of businesses nationwide that have 
been bitten by the pun bug. 
</P>
<P>
Dennis Baron, a professor of English and linguistics at the Urbana campus, said 
Tuesday that what he calls "cutespeak" is a growing trend aimed at capturing 
customers' attention as well as their pocketbooks. 
</P>
<P>
"People are going to be attracted to a place with an outrageous name," he said 
in a telephone interview. "One of the ploys of advertising is to have something 
that sticks in the consumer's mind." 
</P>
<P>
That ploy seems to work for one of Baron's favorite businesses, The Brick Shirt 
House in Croton-on-Hudson, N.Y. 
</P>
<P>
"Originally it was named because it moved into a red brick building and we sold 
T-shirts," said owner Henry Haase. "Everybody laughs when they hear it and they 
say, 'You know what it almost sounds like."' 
</P>
<P>
"It was something we figured people definitely would remember," Haase said. 
</P>
<P>
They did. The business quickly caught on and since opening about eight years 
ago has expanded and moved to larger quarters. But the store has kept the same 
logo -- a little outhouse with a T-shirt for a window. 
</P>
<P>
Dyna Sewer, a Chicago plumbing outfit that calls itself "the rooter giant," 
also says the punny name has helped business. 
</P>
<P>
"You know it does help business because it does attract peoples' attention," 
said dispatcher Dennis Weisenritter Jr. 
</P>
<P>
The company is an example of punmanship expanding into previously uncharted 
territory, because cutesy names used to be reserved mostly for restaurants and 
bars, Baron said. 
</P>
<P>
"You don't think of plumbers with a trendy name," he said, but there's the San 
Francisco-area plumber A Flush Beats A Full House. There's also a mechanic in 
the Southwest called Honest Engines and a gynecologist's office in the Chicago 
area called Ladies First. 
</P>
<P>
These are among the 100-plus businesses listed in a chapter of Baron's new 
book, "Declining Grammar," which examines various aspects of language. The book 
was published in Urbana by the National Council of Teachers of English. 
</P>
<P>
Even Baron thinks puns can go too far. 
</P>
<P>
"A good witticism is enjoyable the first time around, and sometimes the second 
or third time around," he writes. "But frequent repetition sours even the best 
of jokes, and . . . the staying power of funny names is seriously limited." 
</P>
<P>
Some names can even be embarrassing, Baron says. Take the Chicago pet store 
called "Let's Pet." 
</P>
<P>
"What's it like to work in a place like that?" Baron asked. "Do you answer the 
phone and say, 'Hello, Let's Pet?' Or maybe just have the dogs breathing 
heavily?" 
</P>
<P>
An employee who answered the phone saying, "Let's Pet" and identified himself 
only as "Bill" said he didn't know how the store got its name, and referred all 
questions to the owner, who was not in. 
</P>
<P>
Cutespeak can also be too cute. 
</P>
<P>
That was a worry of Belinda Norris and Barbara Bird when they opened their 
Boston caterer, Currier &amp; Chives. 
</P>
<P>
In creating the business 6 1/2 years ago, "We wanted it to be memorable more 
than anything else," Norris said. "I think the only objection on Barbara's part 
was that (the name) might be too cute." 
</P>
<P>
So far, no one's complained. 
</P>
<P>
"It's been an incredible name for us," she said. "People have really responded 
to our name. The phone calls are usually, 'I love your name.' " 
</P>
</TEXT>
