<HEADLINE>
<P>
BRIEFCASE: REAL ESTATE; 
</P>
<P>
SDC DEVELOPMENT AMONG BUYERS OF UNION PACIFIC LAND 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
When Union Pacific Corp. put its massive landholdings up for sale, Koll Co. 
wasn't the only local developer that went shopping. (In the largest deal in its 
history, Koll bought a half-billion dollars worth of land and buildings from 
the railroad recently.) 
</P>
<P>
SDC Development, a much smaller neighbor of Koll's in Newport Beach, paid Union 
Pacific $16 million for an industrial park called Mira Loma Industrial Center 
in Riverside County. 
</P>
<P>
SDC will sell some of the 183 acres at Mira Loma and build factories and 
warehouses on the rest. In all there will eventually be 3 million square feet 
of industrial space at the park with a value of more than $100 million. 
</P>
<P>
"SDC considers the Mira Loma Industrial Center as the jewel of all Union 
Pacific Realty's former properties," Senior Vice President Jim Watson said in a 
press release. 
</P>
<P>
The railroad decided last year to sell thousands of acres and dozens of 
buildings around the nation in an effort to boost its stock price. The real 
estate was worth a lot, but it wasn't bringing in the big money quick enough to 
suit investors. Sure enough, the stock went up Tuesday when the Koll sale was 
announced. 
</P>
<P>
If Koll bought most of the property, other companies like SDC managed to nick 
off a piece or two by getting a foot in the door before the big developer. 
</P>
<P>
In fact, SDC said it wouldn't have minded grabbing a few more pieces. 
</P>
<P>
"There were some other things we were interested in," said Charlie Kanne, vice 
president of SDC's industrial division. "But Koll bought everything they had 
left." 
</P>
<P>
SDC operates mostly in the Southwest. Its biggest project is a joint venture to 
develop 345 acres it bought a few months ago in an industrial neighborhood near 
the Irvine Spectrum, a huge office and industrial park at the junction of the 
San Diego and Santa Ana freeways in Irvine. 
</P>
<P>
Construction on the Mira Loma park, meanwhile, is to begin by fall. 
</P>
<P>
Compiled by Michael Flagg / Times staff writer 
</P>
</TEXT>
