<P>
ARIAS UPSETS NO. 6 SEED IN AUSSIE TOURNEY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
ADELAIDE, Australia 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Unseeded American Jimmy Arias advanced to the semifinals of the Australian 
Hardcourt tennis championships today with a 6-3, 6-4 victory over sixth-seeded 
Mark Koevermans of the Netherlands. 
</P>
<P>
Arias will play Jean Fleurian of France in Saturday's semifinal. 
</P>
<P>
Fleurian defeated Jerome Potier of France 6-3, 3-6, 6-1. 
</P>
<P>
Arias, once ranked fifth in the world, has slipped to 88th on the Assn. of 
Tennis Professionals computer. He did not make the semifinals of any event last 
year. 
</P>
<P>
"You have other things on your mind the older you get, but I want to get the 
desire back," the 25-year-old Arias said. "I want to make one more climb up the 
ladder." 
</P>
<P>
Arias and Fleurian were joined in the semifinals by top-seeded Sergi Bruguera 
of Spain and Austrian Thomas Muster, the third seed. 
</P>
<P>
At Brisbane, Australia, Judith Wiesner of Austria and Natalia Zvereva of the 
Soviet Union advanced to the semifinals of the $150,000 Danone Queensland Open 
women's tennis championship today with quarterfinal victories over the top two 
seeds. 
</P>
<P>
Zvereva defeated top-seeded Helena Sukova of Czechoslovakia 6-3, 6-4 and 
Wiesner beat second-seeded Jana Novotna of Czechoslovakia 7-6 (8-6), 6-3. 
</P>
<P>
Wiesner faces Rachel McQuillan of Australia and Zvereva will play Brenda 
Schultz of the Netherlands in Saturday's semifinals. 
</P>
